ally, please remember that surface mass balance (SMB) is a static measure. It does take calving or dynamic ice-flow into account. \nSo, when someone with zero scientific credentials use only half of the net balance equation to pretend that all is fine (or that Greenland increase) by their PR language, a sceptic should be sceptic and not copy-paste that information.", "recommendation_count": "14", "in_reply_to": "123410267", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "during winter precipitation comes as snow and accumulates while during summer it melts and run off stated", "effect": "this is"}]}, {"id": "123431118", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544135663000}, "author": "fatcat101", "author_id": "100913956", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Zero-carbon growth is possible, and many countries (such as in the EU) have already decoupled emissions from GDP. \nThis is a classic problem for people. The next step globally is to decarbonise gas - thats probably the part you are stuck on.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "123408794", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123430779", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544134879000}, "author": "fatcat101", "author_id": "100913956", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I just hope everyone buys a fuel cell car as soon as they are available. Thats basically what is going to save this planet - and also as I've been mentioning its important that we decarbonise the gas grid via CCS and power-to-gas; which - as mentioned - represents genuine savings if used in conjunction with carbon pricing mechanisms - while also considering the insurmountable cost of inaction.\nWestern countries have a duty to move towards genuine decarbonisation strategies such as hydrogen refueling (major savings on fuel, both in pump prices and due to offsetting imports) and then CCS and power-to-gas via renewables, because it is very affordable - with first movers being able to export technologies to lower-tier countries.", "recommen