ention is now considered to be part of customary international law as well as conventional law. It applies to all actors and must be prosecuted by all states. However, genocide as presently understood would not cover failure to act over climate change. The Rome Statute of the ICC is widely regarded as codifying customary international law [but with exceptions]. \nGenocide does not require \u2018killing\u2019 as such. It may be committed by those \u2018causing death\u2019 and those aiding and abetting such death. It may also be committed by those \u2018causing serious bodily or mental harm\u2019 and those \u2018deliberately inflicting conditions of life calculated to bring about physical destruction\u2019 but in all these cases genocide requires an intention \u2018to destroy, in whole or in part, that national, ethnical, racial or religious group, as such\u2019. [I shorten the description to assist in making a comment as short as possible.]\nSome crimes against humanity might involve environmental destruction if committed as part of a widespread or systematic attack. An example might be deliberate large-scale deforestation. In wartime, environmental destruction, deliberate or reckless, could be a crime.\nIn 2016, the ICC announced it was prioritising crimes that result in the \u201cdestruction of the environment\u201d, \u201cexploitation of natural resources\u201d and the \u201cillegal dispossession\u201d of land.As the law presently stands, in my view doing nothing about or even encouraging global temperature increases would not be actionable as international crimes. \nHowever, [and this is a big \u2018however\u2019] there are several hundred environmental civil cases covering a wide range of claim types presently before the courts. AND, international law is always slowly changing. Much depends on the ingenuity of lawyers and judges in making arguments based on national law and international as well as national versions of human rights. \nI would expect that somewha