e idea of international treaties is to avoid that happening. The present 1 degree warming is the result of a small proportion of nations doing development on the back of fossils. It is tiny tiny tiny. If 6 or 10 billion people do the same 2 century journey this planet is utterly fucked. \nThus everyone agrees that it is only fair that we in the west throw our resources into R&D (and China and India certainly does the same). People will not repeat our history (first car owned by grand grand father - grand father - father - son who finally get an EV). The first car of a huge proportion of families will be zero-emission in the near future. \nSimilar with phones. They do not bother to repeat our history of a century of land-lines before rejoicing in a decade of phone modems, VGA screens and faxes like we did. They go straight to smartphone with 4G internet. \nFact is that we humans have absolutely zero problem with making energy. We know how to make energy out of pretty much everything - including the lunar orbit (tidal). \nThe one thing we humans are terrible at is to store energy efficiently. The best we do is hydro-dams storing kinetic energy. A bit of flywheels (century old tech). And batteries that still are less than stellar in terms of bulk and weight. \nSo what should be the strategy of the upcoming COP is to throw all our R&D into energy storage. We already know how to get energy out of wind (solar energy), hydro (solar energy), waves (solar energy), shortwave radiation (solar energy), fossil fuels (solar energy stored). We know how to get energy out of atoms (nuclear). We know how to use latent energy (heat pumps). And we effing know how to tap into the Earth core energy as well (look at Iceland). And yes, we know how to extract energy from the lunar orbit. \nPoint is that we do not need to invent more ways to make energy. \nWhat we must learn to do asap is to store energy cheap and at scale. Because that is the thing that will fix it. \nFossil fuels has one thing going for it - it is solar energy stored at pretty good energy density. The problem with fossil fuels is that in terms of storing it is really slow. It takes hundreds of thousands of years for the planet to make the fossil fuel we need in a year. This is why the carbon we dig and pump up is typically hundreds of million years old. So it is not exactly sustainable as a resource. And climate change is happening because we so radically intervean with rapid extraction of carbon from a several hundred million year carbon cycle. \nWhat we need to do is to store energy (what fossils learnt). Hydrogen is a good energy carrier - the problem with it is that it takes a lot of energy to get to it - because it tie so well with Oxygen (water is a really strong bond - easily surviving the high energy bombing of solar and cosmic radiation as they float around in space). \nSecondly I hope that they do agree to intensify research on CCS. Not to clean coal plants (that is just silly) - but there are CO2 emissions from making steal and stuff. To capture the byproduct on source is important. \nThirdly I hope they agree to put more money into biochemistry. It is demonstrated that the animals we have tamed over the last 10,000 years can burp much less methane with dietary means. \nWhich leads to the final problem - how to deal with the soils on our planet. We are effing with a lot of sub-fossil molecules. \nBut most of all I hope that by now, politicians realize that their 1.5 degree wishful ambition is just that - a wish. And that the true challenge is to keep the forcing below 3 and 4 and 5 degrees if chance plays along. \nHumans can not do anything about climate sensitivity and feedbacks. We can only do something about our waste-gasses. After 4 decades of being in doubt about how well science has nailed natural sensitivity and uncertainty of ever-increasing feedback-loops - maybe sometimes soon we can hope that elected leaders are able to ponder the millennial scale effects of current 4 year election-cycle policies. \nWe can do nothing about physics. But we can do something about engineering. \nLet us learn to store energy for real.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "123461861", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "we so radically intervean with rapid extraction of carbon from a several hundred million year carbon cycle", "effect": "and climate change is happening"}, {"cause": "it tie so well with oxygen is", "effect": "that it takes a lot of energy to get to it"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "the final problem"}]}, {"id": "123466476", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544222814000}, "author": "JMCBruce", "author_id": "17636726", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Professor W. Broecker, still in his chair at Columbia University told us in 2017 'No amount of emission reduction alone can avoid disaster\" .\nWe don't hear because we delude ourselves that we have yet to run out of road. \nWe base policy on the global anomaly - an irrelevance since he Southern and Northern Hemispheres temperature divergence. Where 90% of us live in the latitude band 44-64\u00b0N, the anomaly is above 1.8\u00b0C. \nWe are not threatened by extinction - we are going extinct. \nBut we delude ourselves by ignoring the data applying to where we live. The data is available at <NASAGistemp> dTs, meteorological ground station tables. \nWe also fudge the benchmarks. We aim to stay below '1.5\u00b0C above the pre-industrial temperature'. But to facilitate 'business as usual' we have replaced that with a GA based on the 1951-1980 mean. Correct the figure and the anomaly is c1.8\u00b0C - above the real pre-industrial 'normal earth figure.' \nI raised these thought with the Met Office who recently issued a press release warning that we would be at 5.4\u00b0C by 2070. We will all be dead long before that.\nWe are not warming at the Paris 2015 predicate of 0.01\u00b0C pa or its 6th October 2018 revision to 0.02\u00b0C but by at least 0.08\u00b0C pa.\n 2018 