iation currently contributes a small percentage globally but it is a high percentage of the transport contribution (~12%) and it is higher % of the UK CO2 emissions (~6%). The reason why aviation needs to be included in our attempts to reduce emissions is that: (a) it's a growing faster than any other source(b) it's especially unfair - in that it allows a small percentage of the population having a disproportionately big CO2 contribution. These wealthy individuals are environmental free-loaders. They are taking more than their fair share of the total Carbon budget. If we had carbon rationing then the wealthy would have to buy quota off the poor in order to fly and then this disparity would become apparent and the degree of inequity would be lessened.If we have such an inequitable usage of carbon then it's very difficult to get the sort of national unity to pull together to cut emissions. There are other sources of inequitable C usage but flying is a major one.e.g. \"As an ordinary bloke, why should I work hard to shave away at my already relatively low emissions when people like XXX on the TV have such massive C footprints due to their flying?\".", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "123432840", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "their flying", "effect": "such massive c footprints"}]}, {"id": "123448679", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544188675000}, "author": "ComfortablyPlumb", "author_id": "14842422", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Indeed - It's not fashionable to say it, but she does deserve credit.\nShe founded the Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research.In point of fact, Jonathon Porritt, head of Friends of the Earth in the late 1980s, says that she: \" \u2026 did more than anyone in the last 60 years to put green issues on the national agenda. From 1987-88 when [she] started to talk about the ozone layer and acid rain and climate change, a lot of people who had said these issues were for the tree-hugging weirdos thought, 'o