ead some new papers that was published between submission and review. \nIn short - science is never able to time a publication date. Maybe Nature and Science have a catalogue big enough to say they can hold a paper for a month for an op-ed on the study and general interest of the subject. But for scientists - publication is around the clock. \nWhat you see is that maybe that general media do highlight science a bit - because all eyes are now on COP24. \nBut if you follow \"Geophysical Research Letters\" and \"Science\" and \"Philosophical transactions of the Royal Sosciety, London\" etc - stuff \"peak\" all the time. Especially when you start to read our special journals like Holocene, Quarternary Research, Fluid dynamics, journal of Glaciology...the list goes on. \nNews pay a bit extra attention when Donald Trump is present (he does sell papers). So it may look like science of climate get a bit extra attention because Donald Trump is not going to be present in the media. Because a political meeting is news. \nBut for science - articles come in at a pace that one simply can not keep up with. Most of them are \"ok\". And the good ones we use year to digest. \nScience do not follow the COP cycles. Or the media cycle. \nAll media looks like science or peace are especially important every fall - when the Nobles go on. Media also look like they care extra much about novels when the short-list of the Booker prize happens every year. But writers do write books outside of that narrow envelope of time. And film makers do make films outside of the Oscar week. \nThere is not a flurry of studies and reports being made by science this week - as little as there are a flurry of movies being filmed during the Oscar week. \nThe \"flurry\" is just pop-culture that media represent. And all the data you see now from science reports are minimum 2 years old. Because first you must submit it. Then you must ponder the review. Then you must wait for it to be published. Then you must wait for science to ponder it before thinking about adding it to the report. Then the report goes on review. And then comes the report that the US government asked for. \nGuardian did always do good in reporting the slowness of science \"news\". That common hard work every day makes news by some regularity.", "recommendation_count": "8", "in_reply_to": "123431601", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "all eyes are now on", "effect": "that maybe that general media do highlight science a bit"}, {"cause": "donald trump is not going to be present in the media", "effect": "get a bit extra attention"}]}, {"id": "123433894", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544147340000}, "author": "Mullah13", "author_id": "13423233", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "This comment was removed by a moderator because it didn't abide by our\ncommunity standards.\nReplies may also be deleted. For more detail see our FAQs.", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it did n't abide by our community standards", "effect": "this comment was removed by a moderator"}]}, {"id": "123433880", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544147260000}, "author": "Mullah13", "author_id": "13423233", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "what is certain is that you can't solve any problem in which you claim there are 200-300 variables but you can't even articulate what exactly the actual problem is in the first place.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "123381706", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123433789", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1544146725000}, "author": "starsmurf", "author_id": "11547449", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "No they couldn't. Poor people would struggle to afford such a diet. Sick and disabled people would struggle for multiple reasons, from allergies to being unable to cook. Certain medical conditions mean following a diet that is incompatible with veganism.\nYour \"simple\" solutions are not possible for some people. It's like the arrogant people who are 