 carbon and local particle polution and what it does to health - we at least can acknowledge that this topic is one that is shared between regions, nations continents and people. \nThe proverbial \"canary\" has long ago moved out the confinement of enclosed \"coal-mines\". \nThe canaries are everywhere. They are in the wild now. The conditions that could kill in small spaces under ground are well emitted into the free atmosphere. A new El Nino is strangely shaping again. Giving another blow to the Great Barrier. Giving new data on what the F is going on in the rain-foreests that show evidence of actually starting to breath out net carbon during observed (not modelled) heat-stress. Or the worrying sign of methane outgassing in the Arctic.\nIt is not nice to read reports of the microbiological processes that help us in our folly are both theoretically and observationally able to become a positive feedback problem. \nSo here humanity sit. Each on our more or less solid ground under local feet that is 30% of the planet. And the problem has one common cause (to be over-arching) - while our individual stories are unique and critical. \nAnd maybe we also see the cause of why solving this is so difficult. Because the problem of AGW requires solidarity. And that topic is not very popular these days as we all run around voting for more nationalism. Pulling out of treaties is way more popular than to sign on to them. \nDistrust is more popular than trust. To the point that I have a feeling that we are now so partisan that if the town-council lay out a perfect plan to end child poverty in the community - half will vote against that plan - because of arguments of identity politics - \"goodness-terrorism\" (an actual word) or \"excuse to privatize\" etc. \nCurrent trends in world politics is moving us further and further away from any kind of solution. To the extent it has become popular to critisize the UN (that does deserve critique always of course). \nBut if we think about th