ationals who can see the medium-long term benefits of informing their customers that they adhere to internationally recognised standards. \nThere is a long list of such initiatives, buying 0Km food etc, non-exploitation of agricultural workers (e.g. in Italy). All of these have come about through peaceful education and awareness initiatives. And, of course, have occurred over a long period and a business case that recognises there are more customers that will consciously make certain purchasing choices.\nPolitical protest becomes more problematic. We cannot compare with the 1960s (Vietnam, Paris etc). There are a stronger biased media machinery and level of conspiracy theory that speeds through the social media and fanatical groups that can hijack a peaceful movement-protest. There are major divisions in frustrations between generations, class and levels of education. The older that hang on to past visions of the role of their country (e.g. Brexit and right-wing/fascist groups in the EU)) and at the same time are witnessing much of the socio-economic fabric that they once enjoyed, evaporating. Most of the young, don't have an inkling of what those benefits were; but as they gradually understand naturally are demanding them or turn on the older generations to accuse. What the older generation (and I count myself) do not fully comprehend is that many young people are much more concerned about global issues (survival of the planet, justice etc) and see us as having created the problem. Simultaneously, many of the youth are awaking to the fact that some of the opportunities that have been created for them are being taken away (e.g. EU in the case of Brexit), moreover, are perceived as being taken away by the older generations. This is also happening in other European countries but rarely mentioned in the press. In the many cases, it is not the majority of the younger generations that are pushing the far-right anti-EU agenda, often it is the far-right older (and include 