r spending increases, the 2 tools of fiscal policy, either of which increases the deficit.\nIf for ideological reasons the government did the opposite, and cut spending to the point of running, or even attempting to run a surplus, all 3 sectors would be monetary drains and recession would be imminent.\nIf the household sector however, meanwhile, had decided to run down its savings and binge on debt, the economy might hold up a bit longer.\nBut relying on increasing household debt is unsustainable as we may be about to learn.\nThe metric you are looking for is \u201cFull Employment\u201d and I doubt there are many who accept that to be 5%.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "123286929", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123294238", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543894762000}, "author": "reinhardpolley", "author_id": "16020012", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Stop guzzling the Liebral's Kool-Aid", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "123293421", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123294162", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543894374000}, "author": "undiscokid", "author_id": "12270676", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Shorten strikes me, paradoxically, as both the biggest drag on Labor and also his biggest asset. The public clearly don't warm to him - if they did Labor would be 10 points ahead in the polls - but he's been a very effective opposition leader. In terms of policy and strategy he's walked all over the government and has maintained impressive unity and discipline on his own party.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "123285797", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123294055", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543893667000}, "author": "undiscokid", "author_id": "12270676", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "A perfect illustration of the attitude Greg is talking about ... so, the main reason you can think of not to vote Labor is they'll give a few people two grand towards buying b