t": "1", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123247958", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543790342000}, "author": "seejaygee", "author_id": "12039812", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Has C1 got leather seats and are they cleaned after Lardarse sits on them?", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123247944", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543790319000}, "author": "JohnArmour", "author_id": "12469905", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nThe difficulty I have with many of the MMT literature I have read is the approach to debt which appears inconsistent with what actually happens.\nBQEND\nIt's the other way around actually. \nIt's MMT that accurately describes what happens, whereas it's the mainstream depiction of the purpose of bond issuance (to fund the deficit) that is inconsistent with the facts.\nTo the extent that all spending carries an inflation risk (a point continually emphasised by MMT), deficit spending is no different.\nBut the main point of deficit spending is to fill in the shortfalls created by insufficient private sector investment, \"excess\" household saving, and the deficit on the current account.\nIt's only inflationary when there's no spare capacity left in the economy. \nMainstream economics claims that by removing the excess liquidity from the system created by the deficit, the risk of inflation is removed.\nBut all the central bank is doing is swapping the excess reserves that accumulate in the banking system from deficit spending for bonds whilst leaving the actual credit balances from the deficit spending intact. \nThe purpose of that exercise is to manage the cash rate, not fund the deficit as commonly believed.\nThe RBA has to buy bonds for its portfolio on the secondary market to enforce \"market discipline\" but which in reality is just to provide a revenue stream for the primary dealers.\nAnd to the extent that bond sales in the primary market are funded from the savings out of previous deficit spending one has to seriously question the claim that bond issuance is even capable of having any effect on inflation.\nBy definition, those savings were sequestered from the spending stream anyway but now earn some interest. \nKeep in mind that the issuance of bonds is a hangover from the era of the gold standard and could, with some institutional adjustments, be dispensed with.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "123229184", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123252563", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543806397000}, "author": "Loco Jack", "author_id": "12150489", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "This comment was removed by a moderator because it didn't abide by our\ncommunity standards.\nReplies may also be deleted. For more detail see our FAQs.", "in_reply_to": "123242476", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it did n't abide by our community standards", "effect": "this comment was removed by a moderator"}]}, {"id": "123252510", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543806112000}, "author": "electricrabbit", "author_id": "12645203", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "This is a government and party that thinks that when the polls are suggesting that the populace is moving left, the way to win them back is to move even further to the right. That even more extreme right wing policies will get the population that's moving to the ALP to stay with them.\nYou couldn't sell a story this mad.", "recommendation_count": "8", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "123258798", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1543831585000}, "author": "rtacord", "author_id": "15473304", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "This comment was removed by a moderator because it didn't abide by our\ncommunity standards.\nReplies may also be deleted. For more detail see our FAQs.", "in_reply_to": "123257811", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it did n't abide by our community standards", "effect": "this comment was removed by a moderat